  {
    "id": 1621359391868,
    "type": "text",
    "content": "\"<h1>Condition</h1>\""
  },
  {
    "id": 1636662065710,
    "type": "grid",
    "content": [
      [
        {
          "id": 1636662074274,
          "type": "text",
          "content": "\"<h2>Live Hard Coral Cover</h2><p>Live coral cover in the ROPME region has ungulated largely in response to coral bleaching events. Between 1997 (when monitoring began) and 2002, modelled average live coral cover declined from 30.1% to 18.0%. This coincided with the occurrence of two severe bleaching events in 1996 and 1998, which caused widespread coral mortality. From 2002, there was a long period of recovery that extended over a decade, with average live hard coral cover peaking again in 2015 at a level comparable to the earliest pre-bleaching records (30.2%). This was followed by an abrupt decline in coral cover to a record low of 17.9% in 2019, which followed bleaching during the hottest summer on record in the Persian Gulf in 2017. Overall, the region has lost 40% of the living coral cover between 1996 and 2019.</p>\""
        }
      ],
      [
        {
          "id": 1636662077004,
          "type": "text",
          "content": "\"<h2>Algae Cover</h2><p>The average cover of algae across the region has been increasing since the early 2000s, from a low of 13.0% in 2003 to a peak of 37.3% in 2018, reflecting algal overgrowth on dead coral skeletons following the summer 2017 bleaching event .&nbsp;</p>\""
        }
      ]
    ]
  },
